nts in the context of changes in ethnic diversity, free trade, globalization, post-modernism, and 9/11. Potter discusses the shifting uses of the terms “liberal” and “conservative” and closes with a look at the current state of Canadian nationalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConservatismzCanada. 0aLiberalismzCanada. 0aNationalismzCanada. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aEmberley, Peter C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrant, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrant, Sheila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPotter, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358216340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773582163423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773582163/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles